  "number": 4641,
  "html_url": "https://github.com/algolia/instantsearch/issues/4641",
  "title": "InstantSearch.js slows down the site",
  "body": "Hello.\r\n\r\ni use [minimal-mistakes](https://github.com/mmistakes/minimal-mistakes) jekyll theme.\r\n\r\nInstantSearch.js loads 20 (!) images for quick search. But it slows down lighthouse and google core web vitals.\r\nCan this feature be removed or configured so that images are requested only at the moment of clicking on the search?\r\n\r\nOr maybe there is an opportunity to tell him to load not 20, but 5 images?\r\n\r\nsource: https://github.com/mmistakes/minimal-mistakes/blob/d6444412c63aea5e47241ef536509fb1bfef4830/_includes/search/algolia-search-scripts.html\r\n\r\n\r\nmy blog page: [https://bitkoinblog.ru/novye-kriptovalyuty/dogecoin/](https://bitkoinblog.ru/novye-kriptovalyuty/dogecoin/)\r\n\r\n<a href=\"https://ibb.co/r5q3Lcg\"><img src=\"https://i.ibb.co/TPJ1nbZ/img-2021-01-29-19-50-37.png\" alt=\"img-2021-01-29-19-50-37\" border=\"0\"></a>\r\n\r\n> The ideal solution would be to defer the load of InstantSearch until the moment the user clicks on the search.\r\nOr postpone rendering of images until the window.onload event is fully fired.\r\nIt might be possible to do just loading-lazy, but Lazy-load plugin does not take images from InstantSearch, so they are loaded on the main thread anyway.\r\n\r\nHowever, 90% of my users will never click on search. So yes, I think we need to think of something.\r\n\r\n",
